ation of GPU hardware was cited as a primary driver of the AI segment\'s operating losses, which widened to **$(2,469) million** in Q1 2026 and **$(6,355) million** for FY 2025.\n\n### 3. AI Segment Capital Expenditures (Hardware & Data Centers)\nWhile the company does not isolate the exact dollar amount spent *solely* on GPUs versus data center shells, the **AI Segment Capital Expenditures** represent the company\'s total spending on compute infrastructure (which is 70% hardware/GPUs):\n*   **Q1 2026:** **$7,723 million** (an increase of $5,156 million compared to $2,567 million in Q1 2025), driven by the rapid expansion and equipping of terrestrial data centers.\n*   **FY 2025:** **$12,727 million** \n*   **FY 2024:** **$5,633 million**\n*   **FY 2023:** **$463 million**\n*(Note: Total company capital expenditures across all segments reached $20.7 billion in 2025 and $10.1 billion in Q1 2026, with the AI segment representing the most aggressive growth area).*\n\n### 4. GPU Market Demand & Unit Economics\nIn its market opportunity analysis, the company quantified the broader AI infrastructure market using specific GPU metrics:\n*   **Total GPU Demand:** Based on an estimated global data center compute demand of 235 gigawatts in 2030 (with 70% utilized for AI), and assuming an all-in chip power consumption of 1.3 kilowatts per GPU (specifically referencing the **Nvidia H100 SXM**), the market will require approximately **104 million GPUs**.\n*   **GPU Rental Rates:** The company applies an 80% utilization rate and a **GPU rental rate of $3.33 per hour** (based on the 2025 median of neocloud GPU rental rates) to estimate the total addressable market for AI compute infrastructure.',
