ce two distinct types of custom chips, leveraging a **"closed-loop single plant"** model where lithography mask design, logic/memory fabrication, and advanced packaging all happen under one roof for rapid iteration:\n*   **Terrestrial Edge & Inference Chips:** Optimized for ground-based use, primarily to power Tesla’s Optimus humanoid robots and vehicle fleets.\n*   **Space-Optimized Chips:** Custom-designed specifically for the harsh space environment to power SpaceX\'s **orbital AI compute infrastructure**. Because manufacturing and silicon defects can cause early-life failures in space, these custom chips will undergo intensive pre-deployment testing and stress-screening to ensure resilience in orbit.\n\n### 4. Timelines\n*   **March 2026:** Collaboration with Tesla announced.\n*   **April 2026:** Intel joins the project.\n*   **April 19, 2026:** The company entered into a compute agreement with Cursor (an AI-native IDE) to utilize its massive compute capacity.\n*   **Future Milestones:** The text explicitly states that specific development timelines, milestones, and capital expenditures for Terafab **"have not yet been determined."**\n\n### 5. Cost Estimates & Economic Impact\n*   **No Specific CapEx Disclosed:** The provided text **does not include specific dollar amounts or capital expenditure estimates** for the construction or operation of Terafab.\n*   **Cost Reduction Strategy:** While exact costs aren\'t listed, the *economic strategy* is clear. By combining internally manufactured, lower-cost chips with third-party sourcing (a "hybrid sourcing strategy"), the company expects the overall cost of its processors to decline over time.\n*   **The "Starship" Analogy:** The company expects Terafab\'s vertical integration to yield massive speed and cost advantages, drawing a direct comparison to how manufacturing ~80% of Starship in-house allowed SpaceX to build the world\'s most powerful and cost-effective reusable launch vehicle.\n\n### 6. Supply Chain & Hybrid Sourcing Strategy\n*   **Complementary, Not Exclusive:** Terafab is not intended to completely replace external suppliers. The company will continue sourcing a "significant portion" of its compute hardware from third-party suppliers. Terafab is viewed as a complementary tool to augment access at a massive scale and act as a buffer against global supply chain shocks.\n*   **Identified Risks:** The company acknowledges severe risks if Terafab fails or is delayed. Without it, they may not have sufficient AI chips to meet orbital demands. Furthermore, they remain vulnerable to third-party fab capacity constraints, raw material shortages (silicon wafers, rare earth elements), geopolitical tensions, and the risk of external suppliers prioritizing competitors over them.',
